\psline[linewidth=2pt]{-&gt;}(-1,0.5)(0,0.5)
\uput[l](-1,0.5){$F$}
\rput(3,0){\psframe[linestyle=dashed](0,0)(1,1)
}
\pcline[offset=-8pt]{|-&gt;}(0,0)(3,0)
\lput*{:U}{$\Delta x$}
}
\uput[u](1,-1){(a)}
\rput(7,0){
\psframe(0,0)(1,1)
\psline[linewidth=2pt]{-&gt;}(-1,0.5)(0,0.5)
\uput[l](-1,0.5){$F$}
\rput(0,3){\psframe[linestyle=dashed](0,0)(1,1)
}
\pcline[offset=-8pt]{|-&gt;}(1,0)(1,3)
\lput*{:U}{$\Delta y$}
\uput[u](0,-1){(b)}
}

            </code>
          </pspicture>
          <caption>
            <para>(a) The force F causes the object to be displaced by <latex>\Delta x</latex> in the same direction as the force. <latex>\theta =0°</latex> and <latex>\cos\theta =1</latex>. Work is done in this situation. (b) A force F is applied to the object. The object is displaced by <latex>\Delta y</latex> at right angles to the force. <latex>\theta =90°</latex> and <latex>\cos\theta =0</latex>. Work is not done in this situation.</para>
          </caption>
        </figure>
		<image style:width='.6'> 
			<src> images/wepmanwithbox.png </src> 
			<attribution> Don Duffield </attribution>
			</image>
			<para> Consider the man walking at a constant speed for 4 m. He applies an upward force of 10 N on the box, and gravity acts downwards on the box with a force of 10 N. For this problem ignore any frictional forces.  What work is the man doing on the box? Explain your thinking.</para>
			<para> Looking at the man, we can see that <latex> \Delta x</latex> is 4 m.  However the force applied by the man on the box is at <latex> {90}^{0}</latex> to the direction of motion.  We can see by applying the formula <latex> {W}={F}_{applied}\cos\theta </latex> that the value of W is zero. So NO work has been done by the man on the box!  Remember that work requires the force or a component of the force to act parallel to the direction of displacement.</para>
			
        <activity type="investigation">
          <title>Is work done?</title>
          <para>Decide whether on not work is done in the following situations. Remember that for work to be done a force must be applied in the direction of motion and there must be a displacement. Give reasons for your answer.</para>
          <list list-type="enumerated">
            <item>
              <para>Max pushes against a wall and becomes tired.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <para>A book falls off a table and free falls to the ground.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <para>A rocket accelerates through space.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
              <para>A waiter holds a tray full of meals above his head with one arm and carries it straight across the room at constant speed. (Careful! This is a tricky question.)</para>
            </item>
          </list>
        </activity>
        
        <pspicture>
          <code>
            (0,-1)(10,3)
\def\cart{\psframe(0,0.4)(1,1)\pscircle(0.2,0.2){0.2}\pscircle(0.8,0.2){0.2}}
\psline[linewidth=2pt](0,0)(3,0)
\rput(1,0){\cart}
\psline{-&gt;}(0,0.75)(1,0.75)
\uput[ul](1,0.75){$F$}
\rput(1,0){\psline{-&gt;}(0,-0.2)(1,-0.2)
\uput[dl](1,-0.2){$\Delta x$}}

\rput{30}(4,0){\psline[linewidth=2pt](0,0)(3,0)
\rput(1,0){\cart}
\psline{-&gt;}(0,0.75)(1,0.75)
\uput[ul](1,0.75){$F$}
\rput(1,0){\psline{-&gt;}(0,-0.2)(1,-0.2)
\uput[dl](1,-0.2){$\Delta x$}}
}

\rput{-30}(7.4,1.5){\psline[linewidth=2pt](0,0)(3,0)
\rput(1,0){\cart}
\psline{-&gt;}(0,0.75)(1,0.75)
\uput[ul](1,0.75){$F$}
\rput(1,0){\psline{-&gt;}(0,-0.2)(1,-0.2)
\uput[dl](1,-0.2){$\Delta x$}}
}

          </code>
        </pspicture>
		<para>For each of the above pictures, the force vector is acting in the same direction as the displacement vector. As a result, the <latex>\theta =0°</latex> because there is no difference in angle between the direction of applied force and the direction of displacement.</para>
        <para>As with all physical quantities, work must have units. Following from the definition, work is measured in <unit>N·m</unit>. The name given to this combination of S.I. units is the joule (symbol J).</para>
        <definition>
          <term>Joule</term>
          <meaning>
            <para>1 joule is the work done when an object is moved <unit_number><number>1</number><unit>m</unit></unit_number> under the application of a force of <unit_number><number>1</number><unit>N</unit></unit_number> in the direction of motion.</para>
          </meaning>
        </definition>
        <para>The work done by an object can be positive or negative. Since force (<latex>F_{applied}</latex>) and displacement <latex>\Delta x</latex> are both vectors, the result of the above equation depends on their directions:</para>
        <list list-type="bulleted">
          <item>
            <para>If <latex>{F}_{applied}</latex> acts in the same direction as the motion then positive work is being done. In this case the object on which the force is applied gains energy.</para>
          </item>
          <item>
            <para>If the direction of motion and <latex>{F}_{applied }</latex> are opposite, then negative
work is being done. This means that energy is transferred in the opposite direction. For example, if you try to push a car uphill by applying a force up the slope and instead the car rolls down the hill you are doing negative work on the car. Alternatively, the car is doing positive work on you!</para>
          </item>
        </list>
        <note type="tip">
          <para>The everyday use of the word "work" differs from the physics use. In physics, only the component of the applied force that is parallel to the motion does work on an object. So, for example, a person holding up a heavy book does no work on the book.</para>
        </note>
		
        <worked_example>
          <title>Calculating work on a car when speeding up.</title>
          <question>
            <para>The car is speeding up and a force of <unit_number><number>500</number><unit>N</unit></unit_number> is applied forward on the car while it is travelling <unit_number><number>20</number><unit>m</unit></unit_number> forward.  Calculate the work done on the car.</para>
			<image style:width='0.6'> 
			<src> photos/WEPThebusybraincar500Nforceforward.jpg </src> 
			<attribution> Photo by Thebusybrain on Flickr</attribution>
			</image>
          </question>
          <answer>
            <workstep>
              <title>Analyse the question to determine what information is provided</title>
              <list list-type="bulleted">
                <item>
                  <para>The force applied is F=<unit_number><number>500</number><unit>N</unit></unit_number>.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>The distance moved is <latex>\Delta x</latex> = <unit_number><number>20</number><unit>m</unit></unit_number>.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>The applied force and distance moved are in the same
direction. Therefore, <latex>{F}_{applied}= 500 \text{N}</latex>.</para>
                </item>
              </list>
              <para>These quantities are all in the correct units, so no unit conversions
are required.</para>
            </workstep>
            <workstep>
              <title>Analyse the question to determine what is being asked</title>
              <list list-type="bulleted">
                <item>
                  <para>We are asked to find the work done on the car. We know from the
definition that work done is <latex>W={F}_{applied }</latex><latex>\Delta x</latex> <latex>\cos\theta </latex></para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </workstep>
            <workstep>
              <title>Next we substitute the values and calculate the work done</title>
              <latex display="block">
		\begin{align}
		 W&amp; = {F}_{applied}\Delta x\cos\theta\\
		 &amp; = \left(500 \mathrm{N}\right)\left(20 \mathrm{m}\right) \left(\cos 0\right)\\
		 &amp; = \left(500 \mathrm{N}\right)\left(20 \mathrm{m}\right) \left(1\right)\\
		 &amp; = 10 000 \mathrm{J} 
		\end{align}
		</latex>
              

              <para>Remember that the answer must be <emphasis effect="italics">positive</emphasis> as the applied force and the motion are in the same direction (forwards). In this case, the car gains kinetic energy.</para>
            </workstep>
          </answer>
        </worked_example>
        <worked_example>
          <title>Calculating work on the car while braking</title>
          <question>
           <para>The car is slowing down and a force of <unit_number><number>300</number><unit>N</unit></unit_number> is applied backward on the car while it is travelling <unit_number><number>25</number><unit>m</unit></unit_number> forward.  Calculate the work done on the car.</para>
		   <image style:width='0.6'> 
			<src> photos/WEPThebusybraincar300Nforcebackward.jpg </src> 
			<attribution> Photo by Thebusybrain on Flickr</attribution>
			</image>
          </question>
          <answer>
            <workstep>
              <title>Analyse the question to determine what information is provided</title>
              <list list-type="bulleted">
                <item>
                  <para>The force applied is F=<unit_number><number>300</number><unit>N</unit></unit_number>.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>The distance moved is <latex>\Delta x</latex> = <unit_number><number>25</number><unit>m</unit></unit_number>.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>The applied force and distance moved are in the opposite direction. Therefore, <latex>{F}_{applied}= 300 \text{N}</latex>.</para>
                </item>
              </list>
              <para>These quantities are all in the correct units, so no unit conversions are required.</para>
            </workstep>
            <workstep>
              <title>Analyse the question to determine what is being asked</title>
              <list list-type="bulleted">
                <item>
                  <para>We are asked to find the work done on the car. We know from the definition that work done is <latex>W={F}_{applied }</latex><latex>\Delta x</latex> <latex>\cos\theta </latex></para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </workstep>
            <workstep>
              <title>Next we substitute the values and calculate the work done</title>
              <latex display="block">
		\begin{align}
		 W&amp; = {F}_{applied}\Delta x\cos\theta\\
		 &amp; = \left(300 \mathrm{N}\right)\left(25 \mathrm{m}\right) \left(\cos 180\right)\\
		 &amp; = \left(300 \mathrm{N}\right)\left(20 \mathrm{m}\right) \left(-1\right)\\
		 &amp; = - 7 500 \mathrm{J} 
		\end{align}
		</latex>
              

              <para>Note that the answer must be <emphasis effect="italics">negative</emphasis> as the applied force and the motion are in opposite directions. This means that the energy is being lost by the car.  This may be energy lost as heat to the environment.</para>
            </workstep>
          </answer>
        </worked_example>
        <para>What happens when the applied force and the motion are not parallel? By using the formula <latex>W={F}_{applied }</latex><latex>\Delta x</latex> <latex>\cos\theta </latex> , we are actually calculating the <emphasis effect="italics">component </emphasis> of the applied force in the direction of motion. Note that this means a force perpendicular to the direction of motion can do no work.</para>
        <worked_example>
          <title>Calculating work done  on a box pulled at an angle.</title>
          <question>
            <para>Calculate the work done on a box, if it is pulled <unit_number><number>5</number><unit>m</unit></unit_number> along the ground by applying a force of F=<unit_number><number>20</number><unit>N</unit></unit_number> at an angle of <unit_number><number>60</number><unit>°</unit></unit_number> to the horizontal.</para>
            <pspicture>
              <code>
                (0,0)(2,2.5)
\psline{-}(0,0)(0,0.5)\psline{-}(0,0.5)(0.5,0.5)
\psline{-}(0.5,0.5)(0.5,0)\psline{-}(0,0)(0.5,0)
\psline{-&gt;}(0.5,0.5)(1.5,2.5)
\rput(0.9,0.7){$60^{\circ}$}
\rput(1,2.1){$F$}
\psline[linestyle=dotted]{-}(0.5,0.5)(2.,0.5)

              </code>
            </pspicture>
          </question>
          <answer>
            <workstep>
              <title>Analyse the question to determine what information is provided</title>
              <list list-type="bulleted">
                <item>
                  <para>The force applied is F=<unit_number><number>20</number><unit>N</unit></unit_number></para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>The distance moved is <latex>\Delta x</latex> = <unit_number><number>5</number><unit>m</unit></unit_number> along the ground</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                  <para>The angle between the applied force and the motion is <unit_number><number>60</number><unit>°</unit></unit_number></para>
                </item>
              </list>
              <para>These quantities are in the correct units so we do not need to perform
any unit conversions.</para>
            </workstep>
            <workstep>
              <title>Analyse the question to determine what is being asked</title>
              <list list-type="bulleted">
                <item>
                  <para>We are asked to find the work done on the box.</para>
                </item>
              </list>
            </workstep>
                         
            <workstep>
              <title>Substitute and calculate the work done</title>
              <para>Now we can calculate the work done on the box:</para>
              

              <latex display="block">
		\begin{align}
		 W&amp; = {F}_{applied}\Delta x\cos\theta\\
		 &amp; = \left(20 \mathrm{N}\right)\left(5 \mathrm{m}\right) \left(\cos 60\right)\\
		 &amp; = 50 \mathrm{J} 
		\end{align}
		</latex>
              

              <para>Note that the answer is positive as the component of the force <latex>{F}_{applied }</latex> is in the same direction as the motion.</para>
            </workstep>
          </answer>
        </worked_example>
